@flexiarg t3/capability-not-functioning
@title Capability, Not Functioning
@sigils [🌱/能]
@audience implementation-researchers, programme-architects, funders, evaluators
@tone formal-analytic
@style design-pattern
@part Open Research Training
@up t3/transformation-space
@see t3/architectural-pair, t3/intervention-triad, liberation/noble/right-view
@tier architecture
@confidence high
@length 180-260
@allow-new-claims false

! conclusion:
  Training produces capabilities — real freedoms to act — only when conversion factors are institutional, not individual. Where the programme produces functionings (attended, delivered, felt motivated) without conversion factors (workload allocation, feedback infrastructure, contribution pathways), outcomes depend on individual goodwill and do not survive the individual's departure.

  + context: Sen (1999) distinguishes functionings (achieved states) from capabilities (real freedoms to achieve those states sustainably), with conversion factors as the conditions that turn resources into capabilities. Open research training gives participants resources — knowledge, materials, motivation — but the question is whether those resources become durable capabilities or transient functionings.
  + if: You want training outcomes that persist beyond the initial event and do not depend on individual goodwill to sustain them.
  + however: Most programme evaluation measures functionings — satisfaction scores, self-reported motivation, delivery counts — without asking whether the conditions exist for those functionings to persist as capabilities. A trainer who has motivation and knowledge but no workload allocation, no feedback system, and no contribution pathway has a functioning; they do not yet have a capability. The three implementation modes observed in this programme are distinguished precisely by their conversion-factor profiles: full (multiplied input), partial (absorbed input), absent (architectural mismatch).
  + then: Design programmes around conversion factors, not just training content. Evaluate whether the institutional architecture creates the conditions under which individual readiness becomes collective capability. Use the five patterns identified in this study as a conversion-factor checklist: Confident Adaptation (clarity), Protected Interaction (structure), Shared Maintenance (distributed stewardship), Contribution Pathways (co-production), Visible Impact (feedback).
  + because: The practice gap in open research is a capability gap in Sen's sense — participants have the resources but lack the conversion factors. The intervention-level patterns (Confident Adaptation, Protected Interaction, Shared Maintenance) improve the resource; the architecture-level patterns (Contribution Pathways, Visible Impact) build the conversion factors. Without the latter, the former produce better-prepared individuals in unchanged institutions.
      + mechanism: Conversion factors operate at the institutional level — they are not properties of the individual but of the environment. A trainer in a multiplied-input institution has the same knowledge as one in an architectural-mismatch institution; the difference is whether structures exist that convert individual readiness into collective practice.
      + counterfactual: If we evaluate only functionings (did they attend? did they deliver? are they motivated?), we conclude the programme is working even where it is producing goodwill-dependent delivery that will not survive staff turnover.
      + applies-when: A programme operates across institutions with heterogeneous infrastructure and cannot control local conditions.
      + does-not-apply: A programme with direct control over all institutional conditions (e.g., a single-site pilot with dedicated staffing and mandated participation).
      + signals: High motivation coupled with low institutional support; delivery that depends on individual champions; outcomes that vary by institution despite identical training inputs.
      + evidence: COM-B survey — motivation M>5.3, institutional measurement M=3.35 (functioning without capability). Qualitative: "At some point I potentially leave with that knowledge and it doesn't get used as much as it could have" (T3) — a functioning that does not survive the individual. Multiplied-input mode shows what capability looks like: "I have integrated it into existing structures of content delivery" (T1) — the practice operates through structures, not individual holders.
  + next-steps:
      - Evaluate programmes using capability indicators (are conversion factors present?) not just functioning indicators (did participants report satisfaction?).
      - Map conversion-factor profiles across institutions before assuming uniform programme impact.
      - Design the operational signals from each pattern as embedded capability tracking (see t3/participatory-evaluation).
  + governance:
      - practice: include conversion-factor assessment in programme evaluation cycles.
      - metric: proportion of institutions where training outputs persist beyond the tenure of the individual trainer.
